tags.comment: XC315101 © J.R. Rigby // Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi (34.3665, -89.5192), United States // 160m // 09:30h, 2016-05-03 // alarm call, call // Natural sound. Two Blue Jays and an American Robin mobbing a Broad-winged Hawk. All three birds perched on bare limbs in the crown of a tree ~7m above the ground. Note harsh Blue Jay calls at 1:23 and 1:40 as the Blue Jay charged the hawk. Besides the occasional sallies by the Blue Jays, there was no other action or violence besides the calls.  /  / #Habitat# / 29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus /  / #Editing# / Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 800Hz /  / #Equipment# / Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.  /  / bird-seen:yes /  / playback-used:no // also:  Broad-winged Hawk, American Robin, Northern Cardinal

tags.comment: XC307817 © J.R. Rigby // Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi (34.4842, -89.5949), United States // 90m // 10:00h, 2016-03-05 // call, growl call, mimicry // Natural sounds. Initially perched in privet in forest understory. Seemed to be harassing a Red-headed Woodpecker, following it from tree to tree and watching the woodpecker while calling. Multiple sounds including typical call, rattle/growl, and repeated mimicry of Red-shouldered Hawk. All RSHA calls in this cut are from the Blue Jay. /  / #Habitat# / State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter. /  / #Editing# / No edits. /  / #Equipment# / Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector. /  / bird-seen:yes /  / playback-used:no // also:  Northern Cardinal, Tufted Titmouse, Cedar Waxwing
